data.name: label7.Text
data.value: · Searching is the technique of finding an element from the given data list or set of the elements like n array, or trees. It is technique to find out an element in the sorted or unsorted list. · There are the following three cases in which an element can be found: 1. In the Best Case, the element is found during the first comparison itself. 2. In the worst case, the element is found only in the last comparison. 3. Whereas in the Average case, number of comparison should be more than comparison in the best case and less than the worst case.

data.name: label8.Text
data.value: -The search method in which an elements to be search is checked in the entire data structure in a sequential way from starting to end is called as linear search. -Linear search is the easiest and straight most searching technique as search element is compared to all the elements in the array in sequence. The searched element is compared with first element which is positioned at index 0 then it is compared with second element in the array which is positions at index1 and so on. If searched element is matched with one of the element in the array then one can print that described element is found else desired element not exists in the array -Let Array[MAX] is integer array in which we have to search an element, Max is maximum capacity of array, is size if array or number of elements in array and item is the element to be searched. To search an element in the array, we have to travel in such a manner that each visited element would be compared to the item. If match found then print the index position and exit

data.name: label15.Text
data.value: Fig 2.6 shows the pictorial representation of binary search. - Let Array[MAX] is the sorted integer array in which we have to search an element, N is the size of the array and Item is the element to be searched. To search an element in the array, we have to compare Item with middle element of array and then find out that in which sub array we have to search. If Item is less than middle element of array than search in the left part of array else in the right part of array. If match found in between this process then print the index position and exit.

data.name: label31.Text
data.value: -In the first iteration 0th element is compared with the 1st element, if 0th element is greater then they are interchanged -Now the 0th element is compared with the 2nd element in the list, if 0th element is greater then they are interchanged. The process is repeated till the 0th element is compared with the rest of elements. During the comparison if the element is found greater then they are exchanged else not. -The process is repeated till the 0th element is compared with the rest of elements. During the comparison if the element is found greater then they are exchanged else not. -At the end of the first iteration 0th element holds the smallest element -The second iteration starts with the 1st element in the list and process of comparison and swapping is repeated. -If there are n number of element in the list then after(n-1)iteration the array will be sorted -The efficiency is given by N(N-1)/2=O(n2)

data.name: label14.Text
label13.Text
data.value: -In this case, after each comparison either the search terminates successfully or the list remaining to be searched is reduced by half. So after k comparison the list remaining to be searched is N/2k where N is the number of the elements. Hence even at the worst case this method needs no more than log2N+1 comparison.

data.value: -Selection sort is the easiest way of sorting. In this to sort the data in ascending order, the 0th element is compared with all the other element. -If the 0th element found to be greater than the compared element then they are interchanged. In this way after the first iteration, the smallest element placed at 0th position. The same procedure is repeated for 1st element and so on. -Definition: Selection sort is the sorting algorithm that sorts data items into ascending order or descending order, which comes under the category of in-place comparison sort. Sorting takes place by stepping through all the data items one-by-one while looking for either largest or smallest data item and making only one selection sort becomes on each pass this algorithm selects either largest or smallest of remaining unsorted data items and places them in the right order.

data.value: Let Array[Max] is array, N is size of array and item is an element to be searched 1. Repeat for i=0 to N-1. 2. If Array[i]==item. 3. Print index and return from loop. 4. If i==N . 5. Print “element not found”.

data.name: label44.Text
data.value: Let the Array[MAX] is array, N is size of array and item is an element to be searched. 1. Set first=0, last =n, mid=(first+last)/2 2. Repeat step 3 and 4 while first<=last and Array[mid]!=item 3. If item> array[mid]then Set first=mid +1 Else if item== Array[mid]then Print ”item found” Else set last=mid-1 4. Set mid =(first+ last)/2 5. If first> last then print item not found.

data.name: label4.Text
data.value: - Binary search uses divide and conquer approach to finds the position of specified value within a sorted array. The prerequisite to search an element in array using binary search is the list should be sorted in ascending order. -To search for an element in the list, the binary search algorithms divides the list and locates the middle element of the list. It is then compared with the search element. If the search element is less than the middle element , the first part of the of the list is searched else the second part of the list is searched -· The algorithm again reduces the list into two halves, locates the middle element, and compares with the search element. If the search element is less than the middle element, the first part of the list is searched. This process continues until the search element is equal to the middle element or the list consist of only one element that is not equal to the middle element or the list consist of only one element that is not to the search Element.

label26.Text
data.value: -In the first iteration 0th element is compared with the 1st element, if first one is greater than they are interchanged. -Now the 1st element is compared with the 2nd element in the list if first one is greater than they are interchanged. -Repeat the procedure until(n-2)nd is compared with (n-1)th element. If during comparison, (n-2) element is found to be greater than (n-1)th element, they are interchanged else not. -When the first iteration is over (n-1)th element, holds the largest number. -Now the second iteration begins with 0th element again and the above procedure Of comparison and interchanging is repeated but this time the last comparison is made between (n-3)rd and (n-2)nd elements. -If there are n numbers of elements in the input list, then(n-1) iteration need to be performed

data.name: label22.Text
data.value: · Bubble sort, also called sinking sort or exchanging sort. · It is a sorting algorithm that compares adjacent pairs and swaps them if necessary causing the items to “bubble” up towards their proper position. This process continues until no swaps are necessary.
